abstract={The default mode network (DMN) typically comprises the posterior cingulate cortex (PCC), precuneus, inferior parietal, hippocampus and medial prefrontal cortex (MPFC) nodes. These regions are commonly reported more active during rest or during a task with little cognitive demand, as opposed to a cognitively demanding experimental task. Besides the pioneer application of PET, two other most recentlydeveloped imaging techniques to study DMN are diffusion tensor imaging (DTI) to investigate structural connectivity and resting-state functional magnetic resonance imaging (RS-fMRI) to look at functional connectivity. Based on RS-fMRI, the highly synchronized regions within DMN consisting of time courses of robust low-frequency (>0.1 Hz) blood oxygen level-dependent (BOLD) signal fluctuations could be detected, and could represent the maintenance of baseline human cognition and metabolic equilibrium. DTI is a measure of the diffusion of water molecules, with the principle that movement of water molecules will diffuse along the direction of myelinated fiber bundles. Besides the neuronal activation and connectivity assessed by using RS-fMRI within DMN, DTI can reveal the axonal conductivity of white matter (WM) associated with neuronal activity in different cortical regions. Regions within DMN are of pivotal importance to daily life, including memory encoding, consolidation and retrieval, as well as environmental monitoring (posterior cingulate cortex, PCC and hippocampus); and higher-order cognitive and social functions (medial prefrontal cortex) such as self-relevance, rapid error identification, and social functions. DMN impairments have been found in several psychiatric disorders, including early Alzheimer's disease (AD), mild traumatic brain injury (MTBI) and autism. For instance, in AD, both RS-fMRI and DTI results confirmed reductions in functional and structural conductivity from the PCC and hippocampus to the whole brain as well as between these two regions, which might be primary factors in episodic memory impairment associated with early AD. The fiber tracts from DTI data indicated a significant correlation with the memory encoding and retrieval tests, suggesting that DTI and RS-fMRI information might be useful in identifying the earliest pathologic changes in the DMN in preclinical AD. Furthermore, a negative correlation between increased WM lesion load and RS-fMRI abnormalities in mild cognitive impairment patients suggested WM lesions may play an important role in cognitive decline secondary to decreased functional connectivity of DMN in the prodromal stage of dementia. In MTBI patients, in comparison to healthy control subjects, the integrity of DMN functional connectivity was disrupted, as evidenced by significantly reduced connectivity in the PCC and parietal regions, but increased frontal connectivity around the medial prefrontal cortex. The reduced posterior connectivity correlated clinically with neuro-cognitive dysfunction including cognitive flexibility, while the increased frontal connectivity correlated with posttraumatic symptoms (i.e., depression, anxiety, fatigue, and post-concussion syndrome). In autism, DMN dysfunction has been associated with decreased volumes of the structures involved, and was one of the key imaging features to be able to differentiate children with autism spectrum syndrome from typically developing children. Taken together, DMN connectivity with advanced imaging techniques enabled quantitative evaluations of neuronal activity and axonal conductivity for studying brain status at rest and under disease conditions. © 2015 Nova Science Publishers, Inc.},
}

