abstract={The default mode network (DMN) was originally identified in PET meta-analysis and describes a set of brain regions, the activity of which is greater at rest than compared with states of reduced consciousness, but also than compared with states of extroverted perception and action. DMN is a specific, anatomically defined brain system preferentially active when individuals are not focused on the external environment. The intrinsic neural activity of the brain manifests as spontaneous fluctuations of the blood oxygen level-dependent (BOLD) functional MRI signal. These BOLD fluctuations exhibit temporal synchrony within widely distributed brain regions known as resting-state networks. This is the review of the structural and functional connectivity of DMN, which has been clarified using PET, fMRI, EEG and MEG. Combining fMRI and EEG, the BOLD signal fluctuations were associated with six widely distributed resting state networks, and were correlated with the EEG power variations of delta, theta, alpha, beta and gamma rhythms. Spontaneous neuronal activity plays a fundamental role in brain function, using EEG and MEG; the stationary large-scale spontaneous interactions will be more evident by considering crossfrequency relationships. These results suggest the evidence of several brain rhythms within large-scale brain networks, and this chapter reviews oscillations in DMN in relation to cognition. DMN consists of multiple interacting subsystems, such as the medial temporal lobe subsystems, and the medial prefrontal subsystems. Raichle et al., first described it as a network comprised of posterior cingulate cortex, precuneus, cuneus, temporo-parietal junction, prefrontal cortex, and anterior cingulate cortex. Recent studies suggest that the hippocampus and frontopolar cortex is also included in this network. DMN is active when individuals are engaged in internally focused tasks including autobiographical memory retrieval, envisioning the future, and conceiving the perspectives of others. These characteristics show that DMN is important to evaluate brain development and neurological pathologies. Changes in the DMN and functional connectivity have been observed in autism, schizophrenia; Alzheimer's disease, temporal lobe epilepsy, and traumatic brain injured patients, and clinical conditions are associated with cognitive dysfunctions in domains that are linked to DMN. This chapter will also review the evidence of DMN that is disrupted in neuropsychiatric disorders in relation to cognitive-behavior dysfunctions, such as attention and memory. Processing of music is distributed across many brain regions including brainstem, thalamus, hippocampus, insula, auditory cortex, limbic system, and multimodal cortical association areas. These areas are known to participate in resting-state networks with hippocampus, cingulate cortex, a part of the default mode network. The music has modulating effects on resting-state networks and that may affect DMN. This chapter is adopted from our original article of experience-induced plasticity and DMN, and also refers to meditation and DMN. © 2015 Nova Science Publishers, Inc.},
}

